Yes, it is possible to upload files to Amazon S3 using presigned URLs through the EvaporateJS method. EvaporateJS is a client-side, open-source library for uploading large files to AWS S3. It also supports resumable uploads and parallel, fault-tolerant uploads. Here's a sample workflow to achieve this task.

1. Install the EvaporateJS library:

You can install it via npm or yarn:

```sh
npm install evaporate
# or
yarn add evaporate
```

Or include it using the script tag:

```html
<script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/evaporate/2.1.1/evaporate.min.js"></script>
```

2. Set up your server-side to provide presigned URLs:

You will need a server-side implementation to provide presigned URLs for your requests. The server-side code can be written in any language; here's an example using Python and the Boto3 library:

```python
import boto3
from flask import Flask, jsonify, request

app = Flask(__name__)
s3 = boto3.client('s3')

@app.route('/sign_upload', methods=['GET'])
def sign_upload():
    object_name = request.args.get('objectName')
    content_type = request.args.get('contentType')

    presigned_url = s3.generate_presigned_url(
        ClientMethod='put_object',
        Params={
            'Bucket': 'your-bucket-name',
            'Key': object_name,
            'ContentType': content_type,
            'ACL': 'private'  # Or any other desired S3 access control
        }
    )

    return jsonify(url=presigned_url)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run()
```

Replace 'your-bucket-name' with your S3 bucket name in the Params dictionary.

3. Set up your client-side code using EvaporateJS:

```js
import Evaporate from 'evaporate';

const evaporateConfig = {
  aws_key: '', // Leave this empty since you use presigned URLs
  bucket: 'your-bucket-name',
  customAuthMethod: async function(signParams, signHeaders, stringToSign, signatureDateTime, canonicalRequest) {
    try {
      const response = await fetch('/sign_upload', {
        method: 'GET',
        headers: {
          'Content-Type': 'application/json',
        },
        params: { objectName: signParams.name, contentType: signParams.type },
      });

      const jsonResponse = await response.json();

      return jsonResponse.url;
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('Error in customAuthMethod', error);
    }
  },
};

const uploadFile = async (file) => {
  try {
    const evaporateInstance = await Evaporate.create(evaporateConfig);

    evaporateInstance.add({
      name: file.name,
      type: file.type,
      file: file,
      xAmzHeadersAtInitiate: {},
      progress: progressValue => {
        console.log('Upload progress', progressValue);
      },
    });

  } catch (error) {
    console.log('Error uploading file', error);
  }
};

// Usage
const fileInput = document.getElementById('file');
fileInput.addEventListener('change', async (event) => {
  const file = event.target.files[0];
  await uploadFile(file);
});
```

Replace 'your-bucket-name' in the evaporateConfig object with the actual name of your S3 bucket.

Now the files will be uploaded to Amazon S3 using presigned URLs through the EvaporateJS method.

