Next, we need to use the Slick-Util library to load and bind the texture. If you haven't already, you should download the Slick-Util library (http://slick.ninjacave.com/slick-util/) and add it to your project's classpath.

Here's the code to add texture to the cone:

```java
import org.lwjgl.opengl.Display;
import org.lwjgl.opengl.DisplayMode;
import org.lwjgl.opengl.GL11;
import org.newdawn.slick.opengl.Texture;
import org.newdawn.slick.opengl.TextureLoader;

import java.io.IOException;
import java.io.InputStream;

public class Volcano {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        Display.setDisplayMode(new DisplayMode(800, 600));
        Display.create();
        GL11.glMatrixMode(GL11.GL_PROJECTION);
        GL11.glLoadIdentity();
        GL11.glOrtho(-10, 10, -10, 10, -10, 10);
        GL11.glMatrixMode(GL11.GL_MODELVIEW);
        GL11.glEnable(GL11.GL_TEXTURE_2D);
        Texture lavaTexture = loadTexture("lava_texture.png");

        while (!Display.isCloseRequested()) {
            GL11.glClear(GL11.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT | GL11.GL_DEPTH_BUFFER_BIT);
            GL11.glPushMatrix();
            GL11.glTranslatef(0, 0, -5);
            GL11.glRotatef(90, 1, 0, 0);
            lavaTexture.bind();
            GL11.glBegin(GL11.GL_TRIANGLES);
            for (int i = 0; i < 360; i += 10) {
                float t = (float) i / 360;
                GL11.glTexCoord2f(t, 0);
                GL11.glVertex3f(0, 0, 0);
                GL11.glTexCoord2f(t, 1);
                GL11.glVertex3f((float) Math.cos(Math.toRadians(i)), (float) Math.sin(Math.toRadians(i)), 1);
                GL11.glTexCoord2f((float) (i + 10) / 360, 1);
                GL11.glVertex3f((float) Math.cos(Math.toRadians(i + 10)), (float) Math.sin(Math.toRadians(i + 10)), 1);
            }
            GL11.glEnd();
            GL11.glPopMatrix();
            Display.update();
            Display.sync(60);
        }
        Display.destroy();
    }

    private static Texture loadTexture(String fileName) {
        Texture texture;
        try (InputStream in = Volcano.class.getResourceAsStream(fileName)) {
            if (in != null) {
                texture = TextureLoader.getTexture("PNG", in);
            } else {
                throw new IOException("Texture file not found");
            }
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
            throw new RuntimeException("Failed to load texture");
        }
        return texture;
    }
}
```

This code loads the lava texture and binds it to the cone shape created earlier. The texture coordinates are defined within the for-loop inside the `GL11.GL_TRIANGLES` block. Keep in mind that this example still uses a rather simple approach and proper rendering of a volcano would be more complex. This code should, however, give you a basic understanding of how to apply textures to a 3D object in Java using OpenGL.

