To answer the part of your question about behavioral and temperament traits, it would be helpful to discuss the general differences between dogs and cats in these aspects:

1. Dogs are typically more social, trainable, and loyal. They are pack animals and often form strong attachments to their human families.
2. Cats are generally more independent and territorial. They tend to have a more self-reliant nature and may not require the same level of interaction and socialization as dogs.

Since C++ is a programming language and not suitable for creating a table, I will provide you with a simple C++ code to determine the average weight, height, and age of dogs and cats, assuming the data is stored in a structured way (i.e., using vectors of structs).

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <string>
#include <numeric>

struct Animal {
    std::string type;
    int weight;
    int height;
    int age;
};

int main() {
    std::vector<Animal> animals = {
        {"Dog", 25, 18, 4},
        {"Dog", 30, 20, 5},
        {"Dog", 20, 15, 3},
        {"Cat", 10, 10, 2},
        {"Cat", 8, 8, 1},
        {"Cat", 12, 11, 3},
    };

    int dogWeight = 0, dogHeight = 0, dogAge = 0, dogCount = 0;
    int catWeight = 0, catHeight = 0, catAge = 0, catCount = 0;

    for (const auto &animal : animals) {
        if (animal.type == "Dog") {
            dogWeight += animal.weight;
            dogHeight += animal.height;
            dogAge += animal.age;
            dogCount++;
        } else if (animal.type == "Cat") {
            catWeight += animal.weight;
            catHeight += animal.height;
            catAge += animal.age;
            catCount++;
        }
    }

    double averageDogWeight = static_cast<double>(dogWeight) / dogCount;
    double averageDogHeight = static_cast<double>(dogHeight) / dogCount;
    double averageDogAge = static_cast<double>(dogAge) / dogCount;

    double averageCatWeight = static_cast<double>(catWeight) / catCount;
    double averageCatHeight = static_cast<double>(catHeight) / catCount;
    double averageCatAge = static_cast<double>(catAge) / catCount;

    std::cout << "Average weight, height, and age of dogs:\n";
    std::cout << averageDogWeight << ", " << averageDogHeight << ", " << averageDogAge << "\n";

    std::cout << "Average weight, height, and age of cats:\n";
    std::cout << averageCatWeight << ", " << averageCatHeight << ", " << averageCatAge << "\n";

    return 0;
}
```

This code calculates the average weight, height, and age of dogs and cats based on the given data. It first initializes a struct "Animal" to store the properties of each animal, and then calculates the averages using loops and conditional statements.

