A skip list is a data structure that combines the benefits of both linked lists and arrays. It is an improvement over linked lists because it reduces the average length of the search path. Like an array, it maintains a linear list of elements, but also maintains links pointing to every k-th element in the list. The advantage of this structure is that it reduces the search complexity from O(n) in linked lists to O(log n) in skip lists, without sacrificing the space efficiency of the linked list.

